  "faqs": [
    { "q": "What is a good credit score?", "a": "Scores above 670 are considered good. Above 740 is very good, and above 800 is exceptional. Lenders offer the best rates to those with 740+." },
    { "q": "How often does my score update?", "a": "Your credit score typically updates monthly when lenders report your account activity to the credit bureaus." },
    { "q": "Does checking my own score hurt it?", "a": "No! Checking your own score is a 'soft inquiry' and has no impact on your credit score whatsoever." },
    { "q": "How long do negative items stay?", "a": "Most negative items stay for 7 years. Bankruptcies can stay for up to 10 years." },
    { "q": "What is credit utilization?", "a": "Credit utilization is the ratio of your current credit card balances to your credit limits. Lower is better — aim for under 30%." },
    { "q": "Can I get a loan with a poor score?", "a": "Yes, but you'll face higher interest rates. Secured loans or credit-builder loans are good options to improve your score while borrowing." }
  ],
